-- South Africa Stocks Rise for Third Day in 4: Billiton, Delta, Exxaro, Move
-- B y   F r a n z   W i l d
-- 2010-10-25T16:19:52Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-25/south-african-stocks-rise-a-third-day-in-four-billiton-exxaro-are-active.html
South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index  rose for the third day in four, adding 144.48, or
0.5 percent, to 30,262.64 at the 5 p.m. close in Johannesburg.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  Austro Group Ltd.  (ASO SJ), a distributor of carpentry
tools and machinery, fell 5 cents, or 9.1 percent, to 50 cents,
the lowest in more than six months. The company said full-year
headline earnings per share dropped between 50 percent and 70
percent.  BHP Billiton Plc  (BIL SJ), the world’s largest mining
company, gained 4.90 rand, or 2.1 percent, to 243.90 rand, a
six-month high. Copper surged to its highest since July 2008 the
London Metal Exchange as the dollar weakened amid speculation
that the Federal Reserve will unveil further bonds purchases
next week. Anglo American Plc (AGL SJ) jumped 6.40 rand, or 2
percent, to 323.90 rand, the highest since April 26. Metorex
Ltd. (MTX SJ) gained 14 cents, or 3.3 percent, to 4.35 rand.  Delta EMD Ltd.  (DTA SJ), which supplies electrolytic
manganese dioxide used to make dry-cell batteries, fell 45
cents, or 4.2 percent, to 10.40 rand, its lowest since Jan. 7.
The company said it ended talks to sell its last remaining
operation.  Exxaro Resources Ltd.  (EXX SJ), one of South Africa’s
biggest coal-mining companies, gained 2.19 rand, or 1.7 percent,
to 133.70 rand, its highest closing price since April 16. The
company said it partnered with Assmang Ltd. to commercialize its
AlloyStream technology.  Famous Brands Ltd.  (FBR SJ), the country’s biggest fast-
food franchise owner, jumped the most in a week, rising 45
cents, or 1.1 percent, to 39.95 rand. The company said net
income rose 24 percent to 109 million rand ($16 million) in the
six months through August.  Harmony Gold Mining Ltd.  (HAR SJ), Africa’s third-largest
producer of the metal, advanced 1.11 rand, or 1.4 percent, to
78.67 rand, a fourth day of increases. Gold surged as much as
1.9 percent to $1,349.30 an ounce. Gold Fields Ltd. (GFI SJ)
rose 1.50 rand, or 1.4 percent, to 106.50 rand.  Optimum Coal Holdings Ltd.  (OPT SJ), South Africa’s fourth-
largest steam coal exporter, added the most in more than a week,
climbing 75 cents, or 2.9 percent, to 26.80 rand. Optimum said
it sees a sustainable increase in demand. The company appointed
 Bobby Godsell  as acting chairman.  Shoprite Holdings Ltd.  (SHP SJ), South Africa’s largest
retailer by market value, fell for a second day, retreating 1.66
rand, or 1.6 percent, to 100.20 rand. Shoprite Chairman  Christo Wiese  said the company is not for sale.  Trans Hex Group Ltd.  (TSX SJ), Africa’s biggest publicly
traded diamond producer, slipped 26 cents, or 7.2 percent, to
3.35 rand, its biggest drop in seven weeks. The company said it
expects to post a 103 million-rand loss in the six months
through September, after making a 9 million-rand profit in the
year-ago period.  To contact the reporter on this story:
